===from:Kara
===email:ckara@nova.edu
===date:Fri Oct 18 14:41:52 2002
===subject:Traditional 
===message:The Makah make an effective argument.  Legally they should be allowed to do whatever they want.  However, whales are important and protected species. They are charismatic and loved by many.  Other countries also participate in whale hunting for traditional and economic reasons. <br>

<p> Traditions are important to many cultures and should be allowed to continue. Easter Monday is celebrated in many catholic countries. People in Indonesia have traditional harvests of endangered trochus shells, but preserve them by only having the harvests in certain years.  Whaling should be allowed just like these celebrations are in these places.<br>

<p> I do not want to kill a whale or be present when it happens. But it is the right of the Native Americans to do what they please in this case.<br.
=========yorg=========
===from:Brock McCracken
===email:sbadfish@aol.com
===date:Tue Oct 22 17:27:43 2002
===subject:Salmon Homecoming
===message:I would like to take the opportunity to tell a story of the Salmon Homecoming Festival held in Seattle on the downtown pier. It was September 1996 when I had the pleasure to observe some incredible pacific northwest native people ceremonies. I will try to decribe my experience as best as I can. It started with an intriguing play on a small stage called the flight of the three seabirds. A concert of drums and carved wooden horns played while the actors danced in eloborate seabird costumes. The entire pier was dotted with booths containing various arts and crafts and information on the well documented struggles of pacific northwest salmon. Several tribes were represented. The center of the pier was a large open space for trditional ceremonies being held throughout the day. One of these was a dance of all the unmarried women, at least one hundred young women participated. They were dressed in their finest traditional dresses with attached bells jingling all over them. They danced under control and wildly at times in constant circles. Often letting out screams. This was truly amazing.
The final ceremony of the day was in honor of a WWII pacific northwest indian war hero who was in a wheel chair. They formed a huge single file line and pushed him around the entire pier meeting cheers from the crowds of people gathered on the pier. After this they all took turns greeting him with hand shakes, hugs, and kisses. Thank You
=========yorg=========
===from:Brock McCracken
===email:sbadfish@aol.com
===date:Wed Oct 23  0:45:09 2002
===subject:Native People's Rights
===message:One should respect traditional customs and practices of native people regarding the oceans and coasts. Governments should as well. Native people have never overexploited the very animals their tribes depended on generation after generation. Animals and water were an important part of their culture and heritage, unlike western society. They often used most every part of the animal killed. The plains Indians had the buffalo until western civilization intervened. It seems the same has happened to the Makah. Cultures all over the world have experienced this.  Western society has over exploited the resources on this planet usually for profit. Trying to make amends today is a start. The interaction between different cultures and knowledge gained from this can change thought processes. What traditional practices are acceptable and which are not depends on the sustainability of that particular practice. If it involves endangered species, usually brought about by pollution or exploitations, then NO.
=========yorg=========
===from:Achim Kretschmer
===date:Thu Oct 24 13:36:09 2002
===subject:Whaling: BAD, Whale Watching: GOOD, but what about Scalping?
===message:Legally, the Makah are allowed to follow their tradition and hunt for whales in their traditional ways. In exchange for their breathtaking coastal habitat they received the legal right to hunt whales if they moved onto a reservation. The fact that a rifle will be used to shorten the suffering of the animal should be overlooked. Were it not for the industrial whale slaughter of the past by Americans, Russians and Europeans, the occational taking of a whale in the traditional manner would not be an issue today. While the civilized world butchered whales, the Makah looked on in despair, and their contribution to the whale population was to abandon their sacred practice of the whale hunt.<p> Morally, it is wrong to hunt whales. The argument that speaks against this particular whale hunt by the Makah is that it is a purely spiritual element. Why, then, kill the whale, if the population is not dependent on the meat anymore? Isn't the spiritual element in the carving of the canoe, the physical and mental preparation, the tracking, pursuit, and symbolic capture (like tagging) of the whale? By the same token, is it not just a defiance by some members of the tribe to rebel against the world to see if anyone dare stop them? They do have the legal right to kill a whale. Will some native American tribes ever think of reinstating their right to scalp an enemy since the act of scalping was also spiritual and a passage to manhood?<p>Whales could be the cash cow to the Makah, not by killing them but by promoting whale watching tours for tourists. If whales really are their friends, let's go and shoot them with polaroids and camcorders.
=========yorg=========
===from:Michelle Cho
===date:Thu Oct 24 15:39:56 2002
===subject:Traditional Practices
===message:This is probably the toughest discussion for me to form a clear-cut opinion about. I think that traditional customs and practices of native people should always be respected, not only regarding oceans and coasts. However, when these practices and customs are destructive to any community or environment, these practices have to be rethought. I like the point made in the video (and also in reply to my last discussion) that humans are part of an ecosystem, and what they do is change their environment. I think I previously thought of humans' overly excessive alterations to their environment as not entirely necessary. However, this way of thinking does not really include humans as part of this world. 
To alter traditions and customs to accommodate changing times and conditions is natural, for safety or humane reasons, and I don't think this is an unreasonable request, as long as the traditions and customs do not disappear entirely (ie there is a written or oral record kept within the tribe, or something else that ensures the changes will not be forgotten). The really difficult part is how modern societies should decide which practices are acceptable, and which are not. I think every practice is unique and must be looked at and treated accordingly. Circumstances are also unique, and while the whaling tradition of the Makah tribe may be able to be altered into a similar sort of physical and spiritual journey without actually killing any whales, I also look at the Treaty of Neah Bay as a reason why the tribe should be allowed to reestablish their traditional practice. Future alterations or treaties may end the practice sometime, but that may take a long time. For now, the tribe should be allowed to continue their tradition. I also agree with Brock that first and foremost, the allowance of traditional practices should depend on the ability of the target species to sustain itself. After that comes the difficult part. This is such a difficult part to discuss because if one practice is allowed, then why shouldn't all of them be allowed? I guess the best thing to do would be to establish a set of regulations that the practices should heed, and then maybe an application process, which everyone would be able to pass, after making necessary adjustments and alterations in order to follow these regulations. This, of course, would be everchanging, to fit the conditions of the time. Wow, I feel like this is so incoherent and babbly, and kind of wimpy, in a way, but I think it is important to be able to back up one's opinion with some sort of solution or suggestion that has a chance of working and appeasing all involved parties, which sounds difficult and at times, impossible to do. I guess that's about it from me for now. :)
=========yorg=========
===from:Jaime Hilliard
===date:Thu Oct 24 19:18:28 2002
===subject:Tradition
===message:This is usually a hot topic and I look forward to a good discussion on this one.  In the case presented in the Makah article, it shows traditional people who where whaling for subsistence and spirituallity actually had the ecological conscience to stop their practices to help the species recover. This tells me that they are aware of the plight of the species and will do what they must to conserve it if their rights are renewed. I think this is a good example of how tradition and modern practices and stresses on marine life can work together.  But in different situations, this can become a horrible debate.  Like the Makah, some tribes have been practicing certain hunts for thousands of years...again...I guess it depends on the status of the animal and if it has a sustainable population or not.  I guess if they can continue their practices while staying between MI and Min, then all can be perceived as "all well".  I was actually thinking about this on a trip into the Everglades a few weeks ago. The Miccosuki (sp.) Seminole indians that live there superceed the laws of no developement and pollution placed upon this wonderful natural area. I was wondering what rights they had and what rights the US government had if the Everglades deteriorated to a level that would question any use. This will always be a heated debate with no decision that makes everyone happy...unfortunately.  If a "traditional" group is taking a small amount of animals out of tradition and some subsistence, then that's one thing, but if they are using their Treaty rights to have an all out killing spree, then that's another.
=========yorg=========
