===subject:Indigenous
===message:I find it amazing that the rights of an "indigenous" (growing or living naturally in a certain place, native, Webster, 1987) people can be so swiftly and readily conferred on certain barrier island tribes such as the peaceful Condowellers, the aggressive Builitheres and the ever-so troublesome Jettycuts . Yet let one 2000 year old culturally enriched society attempt to replenish and revitalize a traditional ritual and the tribulation caused by apparently the meer contemplation of such and act seems to threaten  the very fabric of interspecies relationships on possibly a global if not hemispheric scale.  Or is the hyperbole misplaced?

Doesn't the only relatively positive description of an "indigenous" people making intelligent social and economic decisions regarding a barrier island environmental issue
(the Sebastion Inlet Tax district, Dean,pp90-91) reflect the 
contemplative process of the "indigenous" Mahko?  Do not both societies forsee the encroachment of negative influences on their societies; "the march of houses and condos" as well as, "Drugs, alcohol and unemployment..?"   
