===from:Yvonne Haberer
===date:Sat Oct 26 22:09:12 2002
===subject:Makah Whaling and Coastal Policy
===message:I enjoyed the article "Paddling against the tide" and even explored the topic further on the web.  There are a lot of good websites out there discussing both sides of the debate of Makah whale hunting.  I'm neither for or against the Makah whale hunting and managed to keep an open mind while reading viewpoints of both sides.  

The gray whale is a species that scientists have closely observed for many years.  Once protected, the gray whale populations made a comeback and in 1994 the gray whale was removed from the endangered species list.  

It doesn't appear the level of Makah whaling will pose any conservation threat to the species of gray whales, so why not allow them to continue their tradition?  Technically, the Mikahs have a legal right to hunt whales.  They have a treaty with the U.S. that specifically allows them to hunt whales.  It actually appears that the makah are trying to preserve their culture in a way that is consistent with conservation of natural resources.  

It is similar to seeing the importance of striking a balance between MI and MIN.  You have to remember that human beings are a part of the ecology of the earth.  The role of traditional coastal people has to be figured into the equation of how coastal areas are managed.  
=========yorg=========
===from:Ian Gibson
===date:Mon Oct 28 12:53:12 2002
===subject:treaty rights
===message:I actually wrote a research paper on the legality of the Makah tribe's whaling rights.  As with any arguement, there are two sides.  The tribe has demanded that they be allowed to end their almost century-old recess in whaling, while the world's environmental activist/preservationist groups are wailing away at the "horrors" of the whale hunt. (all the way slamming their fist down upon the emotional touchy-feely push button of the american public) Obviously this is an issue that has inflamed tempers.<p>
However, these environmental groups are avoiding one major point - the US government has an agreement with the tribe allowing them the right to whale.  This agreement vastly predates the MMPA, which i feel, on a few fronts, an  antiquated piece of legislation (re: the effective destruction of the Moss Landing fishing fleet, not by sea or storm, but by beligerent sea lions that can do whatever they feel like without the threat of being asked to leave for other pastures) In any event, the tribe has been entitled to whale, though within the confined of the IWC indigenous peoples clause/quota.  That fact (despite the wailing and gnashing of teeth by Greenpeace, the Sierras, the wacko Sea Shepards, and PETA) cannot be totally denied.
This isn't to say that the tribe is a sweet-natured bunch who simply wants to get back to their roots.  From what i can assess from court proceedings and eye-witness accounts, there are essentially a bunch of angry, poorly educated bunch with serious alcohol issues.  When the first successful hunt occured a couple of years ago, there were several Inuit assistants there to teach and aid the Makahs on the hunt and on the butchering process.  After the whale was killed, the carcass was hauled back to the beach, where there was a brief ceremony where aq small amount of meat was removed and eaten.  Then the tribe took off for a party leaving the poor Inuits to do the bulk of the work.  As it was, most of the meat was wasted.  Evidentally McDonalds is vastly superior than raw whale meat to the native makah palate.  Gross ignorance and incompetance, plus a total misappropiration of tribal rights.  (kicker is they also gave some whale meat to pale-face children at some nearby towns - very, very not legal)
Ok, my rant is almost over.  In this case the US governemnt was pretty much handcuffed.  In the future, the real life viability of tribal customs has to be examined.  Is the custom essential to the culture of the tribe, or is it simply an exercise in flipping the government a collective tribal bird?  These questions have to be asked.....culture isn't a static phenomenon...it is liquid and has to change with the times if nessecary.
=========yorg=========
===from:Ted Kendziora
===date:Mon Nov  4 19:44:04 2002
===subject:traditional hunting
===message:The idea of traditional hunting, in theory, is what all societies should practice.  There are fewer impacts to the environment when hunting is done in a more traditional way, but that is not one of the more major concerns.  My concern is exactly why native people want to be able to hunt traditionally.  Native people are allowed to use modern devices to track and kill their prey.  Some of these animals are considered endangered species.  Why should the government subsidize them because they go out and kill a few animals a year by “traditional” methods?  I use traditional methods when I bow hunt for deer, but the government doesn’t guarantee me a meal or money when I am not successful in my hunt.  In an example such as this I am not in favor for traditional hunting.  Being subsidized for a traditional way of living only to receive money is in all ways completely wrong, but that issue does not have to be carried on any further.  Back to the article about hunting traditionally to strengthen their society.  I feel that it is everyone’s right to be able to hunt, but again it isn’t right for them to say that they are hunting traditionally if the only reason is for them to be subsidized by the government.  It may be a tradition to hunt certain animals to bring spiritual enlightenment, but if an animal is hunted to extinction how enlightening would that be?  Let them hunt in their own tradition, but in order to achieve their goal of strengthening their community, endangered animals do not have to be harmed.  I have had many a day when I left the forest without shooting at an animal or even seeing one, but that in no way has altered my goal of bonding with friends, family and nature.  As I see it native people want their traditional way of hunting back not for government subsidizes, but because of the spiritual enlightenment of bringing their native tribes closer together.  I say it is not the animal that you hunt, but the people that are influenced in the hunt. 
=========yorg=========
